segments.text: That's really what we like to do.
Sometimes we go as far as trying to define the problem.
Most times, the ordinary engineer is involved in solving other people's problems.
Science thinks that there is a... science is something in itself.
It doesn't need application.
In fact, if it has application, perhaps it's already limited or hated.
I once heard a toast given on pure mathematics.
The toast was, here's to pure mathematics.
May it never be of any use to anybody.
And that, in the context of freedom of thought, not constrained by application.
So if you want to define pure science in that way, that's not what we're involved in.
Do you think you're just doing it by application?
Not by application, but to function or purpose.
I always have a bottom line that I'm doing this because it's going to affect this result.
I think science is a very valuable, you've got to have pure, applied, basic, whatever you want to call it.
And I don't know, I don't use the word pure science very much.
People use the word basic science.
And in basic science, at the research level, PhD level, there's not much difference between what an engineer does and what a scientist does.
But I think the bottom line is an engineering research person would have the application or the bottom line purpose in mind as he does it.
So he starts out to do a problem.
And in going along, he finds he doesn't have all the answers.
He can't solve the problem.
So then he looks beyond.
And he doesn't look...
He looks beyond what he's doing and tries to find...
more knowledge about to bring to bear on the problem.
That's what he does.
And so he would expand and hopefully encompass the body of knowledge that will allow him to solve his problem.
If he does, then that's it.
If he doesn't, he'll go as far into magnetic theory or crystal structure or whatever needs to be done in his discipline.
The engineer is working in solid state electronics.
over there doing the same kind of basic stuff as the guys in physics who are in the same field, crystallography.
They're looking at the structure of crystals and how the electrons go over here and over there.
Those guys over in engineering are doing the same thing.
But it's just the perspective.
In science, they're maybe doing it just to understand what's going on.
And in engineering, we're trying to make the circuit work faster.
We're looking for ways to do it.
In my opinion, there's plenty of opportunity to do either one, but generally, in engineering, we're trying to get a job done cost-effectively that sets our, what we're doing, motion.
As an engineer, did you find working with T's cost-effective?
Basically, I didn't know much about cheese.
I mean, I knew of cheese, I knew Harry Whitmore, I knew, you know, but that didn't, I was just my own, the typical engineering faculty member involved in research in a company.
It's a vertically integrated company.
He draws his own crafts, he writes his own proposals, he executes those proposals, he goes to Washington to sell them, takes the money, he spends it,
and he testifies to Congress, and he lectures internationally.
He does all those things, like drawing his own graphs to go into an international forum.
He's in his area, and he's just like this, a slice.
And he's out doing that all around the world.
Now, you come to a point in your career where you would like to

take what you're doing and involve maybe more people or give it some structure and say what i need is a laboratory and what i need is this piece of equipment to make this laboratory go where am i going to generate that that money you say my contracts specify that i'm going to do this kind of research and i'm going to employ these kind of people they almost never have large equipment or space so now you need to go see somebody
is helping you and saying, gee, here's my problem.
I need to have $100,000 worth of equipment.
If I had this $100,000 of equipment, I can generate $500,000 of research a year.
This is going to educate this many kids, this much overhead.
It sounds like a good deal.
Here's your money.
Go do it.
And then you never see them again, except if you don't do it.
Well, how do the researchers come to find out that TEAS exists to do that?
Some astute people find that out in three or four years.
Some dummies like me, it takes seven or eight years that there is the opportunity to do that.
It kind of depends on your own personal...
If you've come here to get that, then you've exposed yourself.
You've asked for assistance, and now the eye is on you.
You've asked for $100,000?
Okay, you've got it.
Now let's see what you can do, fellas.
We're watching.
So...
You want to risk that kind of exposure when you do that.
So that's a certain side of it.
It just depends how mature you are.
Generally, you don't come here anyway without your department head.
So generally, T's would say, OK, go back.
If your department head believes in this as much as you believe in this, you both come to me, and we'll talk about what the opportunities are.
You really can't afford to deal with 500 different faculty members on a day-to-day, personal basis until you deal with the department head.
That's really been the key that you can't be affected.
The department head then makes some judgment and say, you know, I'm doing about a million dollars worth of research.
TEAS probably shouldn't be able to support me about 10% of that or something.
So this year I might be able to ask for $100,000 to make new things happen.
And if I ask for it all for this guy, then I'm not going to be able to come back again.
So I better believe in it.
And if the department head believes in it, and then comes with you to get the money, and the faculty member knows it's a worthwhile thing, the department head dies, and he can get .
As an engineer, and as someone doing research,
Did you, how did you personally realize that TUES was here?
Well, in my case, we were one of the departments that had a separate, every department head is a TUES division head.
In engineering.
In engineering, right.
So the department head of electrical engineering is the department head and the division head for TEAS research.
So you know, and he's the main interface.
You really work with the department head.
And the department head works for two people.
When he wants to get research money, he works for the experimentation.
When he wants to get some new courses, he works for the dean.
So you know that.
In some departments' cases, in the early days,
There was somebody from this office who was really the division head.
And the department head wasn't interested in research, for example.
He said, we don't really need too much research.
Then there was another person.
And Dr. Bain was the representative from the Ingenic Experiment Station who helped us with research.
So he would visit every month or so and come around and talk to you.
So that was the structure.
money paid to the director or to the heads of the departments coming from TEAS?
Sure, right.
Generally, one quarter of the salary is put aside.
And it's up to them if they would like to.
They get so much money.
And if they would like to put themselves on the payroll, that's fine.
If they would like to save that money and teach more courses themselves and give that money to junior faculty, that's great.
But if they do put themselves on time and get release time to do this.
Right.
But it's there.
And in part of his case, he releases himself.
Yeah.
But he feels that his time is best invested.
Sure.
How do you feel the role of teams has changed in terms of dissemination of information?
There was a period of time
many, many years ago when engineering experimentation used to make official publications on the work they did.
And as far as I could tell in the 70s, that wasn't done.
I think in 81, we got Penny Beaumont to come over and reestablish our information services.
And I think the dissemination of information has improved vastly, but I think it's nowhere near
Have we been able to disseminate information on the level we should, and as effectively as we should?
We're now doing a number of things.
For example, we have abstracts in our Windows publication of recent Keyes' publications.
We started a research library that we're going to catalog and house.
We started the Keyes monograph series, which is going to see
a report or a paper dealing with a single topic.

And while it may be technically very advanced and very interesting, to be really useful to the next level of working person, such as a consulting engineer or whoever it might be, it needs to be put together a little bit.
So what I've been looking for is opportunities to take those people working in an area four or five years.
that understand that they've written four or five papers, put that together in a format that's going to be useful from then on, but not just be isolated topics.

So that's what the purpose of the Thieves Monograph Series is, to take this mature research body of work, put it together in a form that is now permanent and useful as reference material for the rest of the world.
So we're just trying different niches and trying to fill those niches.
And we've started on several areas, but I think there's a lot more we have to do.
Are there any other particular programs that I haven't asked you about that you remember as being partisan?
Over the years?
Mm-hmm.
No, I really can't think of too many.
The one that's recent is our T-cells program.
I don't know if you've heard of that.
I've read about it, but no one's ever told me about it before.
Again, in the structure that we're in, very often it's
easy to have a situation where a guy's been working his heart out for 10, 20 years, and nobody really knows.
And on the one hand, he worked for TEAS.
And on the one hand, he worked for the university.
And the university says, well, he does his research at TEAS.
So TEAS should do whatever recognition should be done.
And on the other hand, TEAS says, well, he's a faculty member.
We're just here to provide a few opportunities.

So when I came over, one of the things that I thought might be useful in making everybody feel like there was a team and that research over the long period was valuable and rewardable is I started the Monograph Series and I started the Teeth Fellows Program.
The Teeth Fellows Program was endowed
tease money at a million dollars to produce roughly $100,000 a year.
And what we do with that is look for the top 20 researchers in the experiment station and give them a $5,000 award for anything they want to do that is legal in the state.
Many of them are buying their own computers that they take home, and then they work at home, plug into, you know, really it's a great investment.
Some of them do international travel, or both.

But the point is, they don't have to, when an opportunity comes up, they don't have to ask the department head for money, they don't have to ask us for money, they don't have to ask anybody for money.
They just go and do it.
This is $5,000 to apply to their research?
Research and professional development, right.
And $5,000 of the flexible money is, say, worth a $50,000 contract because it is entirely flexible.
And so we have done two years now of this.
We started out with 12, and then we now have 20.
About two of those are...
visiting people, so it gives an opportunity to attract people to come here from Germany or France, wherever the coverage are.
Most of those are for the senior type researchers that I've already explained that have given a lifetime of research, and this is a reward.
And then a small amount of them for Bible, to recognize extremely bright young kids.
And give them a little, say, gee, you're doing good, you know, you're not perfect, but go do some more.
And so that's what we've been using it for.
And we meet two or three times a year with them, have luncheon and so forth.
And we have no pressure on them to perform anything.
Just to give them a feeling they're part of a professional team and their work is recognized and appreciated.
And I think it's built a lot of good feeling and helped to develop a less competitive environment for them to be working together.
We charge those fellows, especially the senior ones, their job, if anything, is to act like a steward to the younger faculty and bring them along.
If they're looking for something to do, be a mentor.
So that's what we approach them with.
I think that has helped the visibility team.
Yes.
Right.
These two things were ideas that I had that I thought would improve the visibility, improve
prove the fact that, you know, a lot of people would say, well, geez, all they want to do is just get a lot of research, and they're not really interested in what the research is.
And, you know, in the bottom line, there's always that element to it, but I thought that might break that a little bit and give a little better feeling about that.
Who chooses these folks?
We have a system-wide committee.
It's a proposed representative of the president's office using Charlie McCann and Chuck McCann.
I'm a representative of the dean's office.
Two TEAS division heads, which I rotate, and myself.
And we take in 40, 50 nominations from the division heads.
We evaluate it.
And it's not only open to faculty.
We have a senior researcher.
His name is Reed.
He's a Korean guy that's been here many years and worked for the Food Protein Center.
We have two from the College of Business.
We have a business technology group.
We have Dr. Daft, and Dr. who stays in director of that thing.
We have two from there.
So it's not just engineering, it's T's wide, but it's mainly engineering.
Has the interdisciplinary aspect changed much?
Well, it's a very difficult thing to do.
You probably know.
But it is a unique thing that we can do that never fails to excite people from the outside.
If you tell them that you're capable of involving multidisciplinary teams, they just think that's terrific.
They don't see that at other universities.
Frankly, it's a very difficult thing to do.
If we do do it, we don't do it as successfully as we'd like to.
There's a lot of pressures to compartmentalize things.
But it's a very valuable and useful thing, certainly in engineering, to be able to do this.
You can begin to look at much more complex, more meaningful problems if you're able to do that.
You can't look at a problem like water.
Has this striving for interdisciplinary cooperation been here since you've been here?
more strong lately.
It's something that we're trying to do.
I think it's beginning to be recognized that we're trying to keep those paths open.
Like I said, it's difficult.
Is there anything else you'd like to add about TEAS or its role or anything that I haven't asked you about?
I think you asked some good questions.
No, I don't know if there's anything useful and
I think, I hope I've told what I think is the real story of research and how TEAS is not.
TEAS is basically individual faculty members doing what they want to do.
And we provide the umbrella.
The university is the same thing, way too.
The university may say they're doing a whole bunch of stuff.
What it is is a bunch of individuals working for themselves
in more or less loosely connected areas.
And that's not bad.
But that's easy the same way, except even more so, because the element of proof is the international and national competition.
We direct very little.
But the amount that we do have to direct, we unfailingly do in a very leveraged way.
In other words, we start things.
get them going, but we never stand back and say we're going to pay for this operation for the next 20 years out of our limited resources.
It can't really fly its own one way or the other, and it probably doesn't need to be here, or it needs to be at the University of Columbia, and they'll make it free.
Okay.
Thank you for your time.
